      <section id='code_of_conduct'>
        <h2>Code of Conduct</h2>
        <p>Since every developer should enjoy the benefits of testing their own code, it's important that Test Ruby PDX be a space where everyone feels safe and welcome. The following are some guidelines suggesting appropriate and inappropriate behaviors. Violations will be handled on a case-by-case basis, but be aware that you may be asked to leave if your behavior is out of line. <strong>Our guiding principle is "Be kind."</strong> If you have to ask if you're being a jerk, the answer is probably yes.</p><br><br>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>DO welcome everyone.</strong> We anticipate a diverse audience and encourage you to make connections with other people regardless of their race, national origin, religion, sexual orientation, gender identity/expression, physical appearance, disability, socioeconomic background, and other personal characteristics of that nature. They'll feel more welcome and you may well learn some new things about coding, testing, or life in general.</li>
          <li><strong>DO treat others how you'd like to be treated.</strong> Most of us want to be welcomed into a group, to feel like we fit in, to be called by the name and pronoun we want, to be treated like competent adults, and not to be subjected to the ridicule of our peers. Please keep this in mind when you're interacting with other people.</li>
          <li><strong>DO recognize everyone has different sensitivities.</strong> If someone reacts to something differently than you do, it might not be that they are overreacting. Instead, they might be responding reasonably in the context of their life experiences. Please do your best to anticipate what those sensitivities might be and respond accordingly.</li>
          <li><strong>DO behave your best regardless of who is in attendance.</strong> If you wouldn't say something or act a certain way in front of certain people, you probably shouldn't do it when they aren't there either.</li>
          <li><strong>DO take criticism in stride.</strong> Corrections like, "Actually, the pronouns I use are 'she' and 'her'," are not attacks. Your response to them should be to apologize and do better in the future. 
          <li><strong>DON'T use language commonly used to disparage particular people or groups.</strong> This includes sexist, racist, heterosexist, and cissexist words and stereotypes (even if you think the stereotype casts the group in a positive light).</li>
          <li><strong>DON'T harass people, sexually or otherwise.</strong> If someone has asked you to stop doing whatever you're doing - <em>or if you notice they don't like what you're doing</em> - stop and apologize, even if it seems unreasonable to you. Then remember, they are not under any obligation to accept your apology or interact with you in the future.</li>
        </ul>
